description: This course is designed to teach students the art and science of audio editing using Adobe Premiere Pro. Through hands-on practice and creative projects, students will learn how to clean, enhance, and synchronize audio for various media applications, as well as creatively design a scene using sound design as a critical element of the mise en scene. By the end of the course, Students will have a portfolio of polished audio projects and a solid understanding of professional audio editing techniques with option to take advanced level. Prerequisite(s): COMM 1120 or 1125 ST:Sonic Storytelling 2 in MT2 or Spring 26

This course is an advanced level sound design course of audio editing for multiplatform content and motion pictures using Adobe Premiere Pro and AVID. Students will learn advanced audio techniques for various media applications, as well as creatively design productions with sound from script to screen. By the end of the course, students will have a portfolio of polished audio projects using advanced professional audio editing techniques. Prerequisite(s): COMM 4454- ST: Sonic Storytelling 1

This course will explore how and why innocent individuals can be arrested and convicted for crimes they did not commit as well as what our criminal justice system does to address and/or rectify these errors. We will examine the leading causes of wrongful convictions and the procedural measures that can be implemented to protect against or prevent future mistakes. We will study some Innocence Project cases and delve into the challenges faced by exonerees , their family members, and crime victims when an exoneration occurs. This course is intended for upper-level students who have completed one or more of the following: Criminal Procedure I (CJST-221 7), Introduction to Legal Concepts (LSTD 1100), or Constitutional Law (PSCI 3332 ).

course_name: ST: Costs of a Criminal Record
description: This seminar examines the far-reaching consequences of a criminal record on individuals and society. The course will explore how a criminal record affects employment, housing, voting rights, family , family dynamics, and social integration. It will also evaluate the broader societal impacts, including public safety, recidivism, and economic costs. Students will engage with current research, policy debates, and case studies, while assessing the effectiveness of various rehabilitation and reintegration strategies. The course will challenge students to think critically about fairness, equity, and the broader social implications of criminal justice policies, preparing them for roles in criminal justice, social work, law, or advocacy.
Students are required to complete HNRS 1112, ENGL1112, ENGL1113 or ENGL1114 prior to enrollment in this section.
